<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n18053e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n18" href="#n18053e">N18 (VI.B.8)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n18all.htm#n18053e"> 53(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> horizon blue</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Threading his way through all this new world of men, marching or strolling with the nonchalant step of the man who treads his own home soil, you would have met the poilu, in his <mark>horizon blues</mark>, little dreaming, so long as the war was on, of the hero buttoned up within his ill-fitting uniform. His discovery of his value has come later&mdash;as the disconcerting protest of repeated strikes has proved to an amazed world. <small> Anna Bowman Dodd, <a name="ABDU" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ABDU"><cite title="source">Up the Seine to the Battlefields</cite></a> (1920) 16</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Fr. <i>Bleu horizon</i>. A light shade of blue, the colour of the uniform of the French Army during and after the war of 1914-18; such a uniform; also as adj. (<cite>OED</cite>) </mm> </dd></dl>
